<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-039-090 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 488 752</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Business  Oct 7 1991 v17 n19 p206(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The Baldrige will fail unless more companies participate. (MalcolmBaldrige National Quality Award)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Russell, John.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Some industry experts contend that the Malcolm Baldrige NationalQuality Award may not be an effective way to enhance product andorganizational quality among US industries because very fewcompanies elect to enter the competition.andP;  Research indicates thatonly 106 companies entered the contest in 1991.andP;  Supportersbelieve the contest promotes the discussion of quality throughoutthe US, but the award is in danger of losing its effectiveness ifmore companies do not take part.andP;  More firms would enter if aguaranteed payoff could be developed.andP;  For example, firms thatreach a set level of excellence as determined by Baldrige rulesand regulations could then receive a short-term research anddevelopment tax credit or elect to speed-up capital equipmentdepreciation schedules.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Achievements and AwardsTax DeductionCompaniesMalcolm Baldrige National Quality AwardUnited States. Department of Commerce.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>